When the observed values are not correct, the inference based on them are incorrect as well, and then, it is evident that the implications can be very serious. In this situation, it is necessary to treat the observed values in order to reduce the errors that could exist. Analyzing the observed values, it is possible to detect the existence of some errors or inconsistencies. In the initial pandemic period (the first wave), data were subject to mistakes of different kind coming, for example, from incorrect registrations, duplicity or delays in the communication, with the corresponding rectifications and corrections, as we can see in [46, 47] or [48]. Then, the treatment of the initial series is necessary, but not only in relation to the corrections of the Spanish government but also to technical (and reasonable) aspects such as the continuity of the series or the magnitude of the values in adjacent times, which should be similar. Figures 5 and 6 show for the variable \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
